, 0.0346098355948925, -0.059840936213731766, 0.02982896752655506, 0.03078971616923809, -0.0054185097105801105, 0.045612700283527374, -0.004028854891657829, 0.022760599851608276, -0.04785444959998131, -0.010396676138043404, 0.022874975576996803, -0.03955083340406418, 0.028959717601537704, 0.03950508311390877, -0.006799586582928896, -0.026374846696853638, -0.012970111332833767, 0.008898365311324596, 0.020084228366613388, 0.0016770216170698404, -0.008738240227103233, 0.03289421275258064, -0.011237331666052341, 0.0578736886382103, 0.018883291631937027, 0.0007062648655846715, 0.01671016961336136, 0.022623350843787193, 0.0004417729505803436, 0.004489213693886995, -0.03394646197557449, -0.0016512873116880655, -0.00022785620240028948, -0.006770992651581764, 0.00790330395102501, -0.017339231446385384, -0.011391737498342991, 0.04222720488905907]], "input": ["\"BOTTLENECK RESOURCE\":A Bottleneck Resource is a resource that limits the overall output of a production process due to its limited capacity. It is the part of the production process that has the least capacity and, as a result, restricts the overall output of the system.", "\"WORK-IN-PROGRESS (WIP)\":\"Work-in-Progress (WIP) refers to the materials and components that are in the process of being transformed into finished products.\"", "\"CAPACITY CONSTRAINT RESOURCE (CCR)\":\"A Capacity Constraint Resource (CCR) is a resource that, while not the primary constraint, has the potential to become a bottleneck if not managed properly.\"", "\"THROUGHPUT\":\"Throughput is the rate at which a system generates money through sales, and it is a key focus in the Theory of Constraints.\"", "\"OPERATING EXPENSES\":\"Operating Expenses are the costs associated with running a business, excluding the cost of direct materials.\"", "\"INVENTORY\":\"Inventory refers to the raw materials, work-in-progress, and finished goods that a company holds to support production and sales.\"", "\"PRODUCT MIX\":\"Product Mix\" refers to the variety and quantity of different products that a company produces and sells. It encompasses the total range of products that a company offers to its customers.", "\"FACTORY HOUR\":\"Factory Hour is a measure of the time a factory or production line is available for production.\"", "\"RETURN PER FACTORY HOUR\":\"Return per Factory Hour\" is a metric used to determine the profitability of products based on the time they spend in the production process. It is calculated as the throughput per unit divided by the hours of bottleneck resource used per unit.", "\"OPTIMUM PRODUCT MIX\":\"Optimum Product Mix\" refers to the combination of products that maximizes profitability within the constraints of the production process. Specifically, it is the combination that maximizes net profit given the limitations of production capacity and bottlenecks. In practical terms, this involves producing and selling product B up to its maximum demand and then utilizing the remaining capacity to produce product A.", "\"CONSTRAINT\":\"A Constraint is any factor that limits the performance of a system and restricts its output.\"", "\"NON-BOTTLENECK RESOURCE\":\"A Non-Bottleneck Resource is a part of the production process that has more capacity than the bottleneck and does not limit the overall output.\"", "\"THROUGHPUT PER BOTTLENECK HOUR\":\"Throughput per Bottleneck Hour is a measure of the throughput generated for each hour the bottleneck resource is utilized.\"", "\"SALES REVENUE\":Sales Revenue is the income generated from selling goods or services before any costs or expenses are deducted. It serves as a primary indicator of business performance and is used to assess profitability and growth. The total revenue generated from sales is $9.20 per customer.", "\"DIRECT MATERIAL COSTS\":\"Direct Material Costs are the expenses directly associated with the production of goods, such as raw materials.\"", "\"FIXED COSTS\":\"Fixed Costs\" are expenses that do not change with the level of production or sales. These costs remain constant regardless of the business activity level and include items such as rent, salaries, heat and power costs, fixed machine costs, depreciation, and insurance costs. While fixed costs are generally irrelevant to decision-making unless there is an incremental step in the fixed cost, they can be considered in decision-making when they can be avoided or reduced as a result of the decision."], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}